#### QUESTION 2 (0.5 Points).

Split cancer data into 70% training and 30% testing using a stratified
random sampling using the createDataPartition() function that comes with
caret package Explain why this approach of splitting data is better than
completely random split. Develop an MLR to predict Area using all other
variables as independent variables in TRAINING data Interpret model
goodness of fit. Is this regression model a good fit for the observed
data? Why or why not? Explain in your own words.

```{r}
library(caret)
set.seed(123)  # DO NOT CHANGE THE SEED - for reproducibility of the random split
index <- createDataPartition(cancer$Area, p =  0.7, list = FALSE)
traincancer <- cancer[index, ]
testcancer  <- cancer[-index, ]
model_c <- lm(Area ~., data = traincancer)
summary(model_c)
```

#### Interpretation:

1.  Having a standardized data partition such as 70:30 is better than a
    completely random split because the defined split ensures we have a
    deliberate balance between training data and testing data thereby
    reducing overfitting.

2.  Looking at our summary, this is model is a good fit for our data.
    Our R-squared value is very close to 1, i.e., 0.8729, which implies
    a huge portion of the variation (87%) can be explained by the model.
    The adjusted R-squared is also very close to 1, i.e., 0.8703, which
    means that the model explains a huge variation in the dependent
    variable, 'Area' around its mean.

